AB  - U.S. Bureau of Mines Report of Investigation 8507 was published in 1980. In a comprehensive analysis of all known blast damage studies plus new definitive data, the USBM authors adopted new safe level criteria of 0.5 & 0.75 in/sec for the frequency range corresponding to structure resonances. These were 3 to 4 times lower than the existing limit of 2 in/sec and are the most restrictive scientifically-based blasting criteria for the prevention of threshold hairline cracks in homes. The Bureau's own tests involved 76 homes in six states. In USBM RI 8507, those tests were combined with data from nine other studies from the US, Canada, Czechoslovakia and Sweden in an overall conservative summary analysis intended to preclude blasting damage.
   Since the publication of RI 8507, the following additional work was either completed or found. These studies support the safe-level criteria in RI 8507 as protective of structures from all blasting damage:
   Cracking and responses from blast vibration:
   A four-site USBM study of response and damage from low-frequency vibrations
   A seven-part fatigue study by the USBM, which also involved two Universities (Northwestern and Drexel) and two other Federal science labs (Bureau of Standards and Corps of Engineers)
   Additional blasting damage studies in England (Leeds University) and India (Ctrl. Mining Res. Station)
   An extensive study of structure responses from sonic booms by the FAA
   Natural and cultural stresses on homes:
   14 Reports or studies of weather-induced stresses from temperature & humidity
   9 Reports of soils, water and slope effects on foundations and pavements
   3 Reports which describe vibrations in homes from inside activities
   3 Reports related to construction characteristics
   The RI's criteria have been variously challenged in the 17 years since publication. Initial concerns were from industry, believing them to be too restrictive and not justified. More recently, claims have been made in courts, permit hearings, and by legislators that they are not protective enough. Technical reasons are sometimes given, but, all real issues such as low frequencies, fatigue, and preexisting strains, have been examined. The remaining concerns arise from cases of large numbers of claims and complaints from organized citizen groups. These are issues of perceptibility and attitude. Based on the science and all objective measures, the criteria in RI 8507 are still believed to represent appropriate, if not conservative, guidance for the prevention of threshold cosmetic cracking in homes.
