AB  - The diesel engine offers a very attractive option for road transportation It is intrinsically robust, clean and efficient, and is therefore increasingly popular worldwide.
   Environmental concerns are driving towards lower exhaust emissions, and the diesel engine star ts from a good position in that its hydrocarbon, nitrogen oxides and carbon monoxide emissions can only be matched by gasoline engines equipped with three way catalysts. However, particulate emissions are a con cern and this is the main driving force towards tighter diesel fuel specifications.
   These two factors - increasing demand for diesel fuel and tighter specifications - may conflict with one another because the processing required to improve quality reduces the gasoil yield on crude and thus the availability of diesel.
   Shell has developed a portfolio of hydroprocessing technologies to upgrade the quality of gasoil components at very high yields. These technologies can meet the highest quality demands as, for example, demonstrated in Sweden by the commercial production of Class I Gasoil (Green Diesel) at the Gothenburg refinery.
   However, application of these advanced technologies should be assessed carefully. Cost increases rapidly, not only in capex and opex, bur also in terms of energy requirements, CO2 emissions and diesel availability. Environmental benefits im prove only gradually or not at all; for example, it has been shown that reducing the aromatics content has no effect on particulate emissions. Therefore a balanced approach is needed, taking all factors into account (cost, air quality, equipment & fuel developments), and it should be appreciated that as a result the optimum solution will differ across the world.
