AB  - This study focused on classification of sample plots on a peatland ecosystem in Southern Finland using remote sensing. A new hierarchical peatland classification system was developed consisting of four classification levels, and in which two, two, seven and sixteen biotope types were included. The study area was at Lakkasuo near the Forestry Field Station of Helsinki University in Southern Finland. 496 plots were sampled and measured using 50 meter square grids. Estimates were based on 250 plots and 246 plots were used for testing. Traditional peatland classification was used as a starting point and refinements to the classification were further made using remote sensing data. The auxiliary data included digitized blue, green and red channels obtained by scanning a negative infrared aerial photograph taken in 1995. For comparison, Landsat TM images of seven channels taken in 1995 were also used.
   The method is similar to two phase sampling for unsupervised stratification. Optimal window size for obtaining the window values from the digital aerial photos for each biotope type in the classification system was studied. The effectiveness of classifying peatland ecosystems using digital aerial photos were assessed. The effect of location variables including photo coordinates, distance between plots, the principal point of the photo, and azimuth, zenith and camera angle of plot were analyzed for calibration purposes. Texture features from digital aerial photos were analyzed and used for stratification. The window values and texture features from the digital aerial photos, and the radiation values from TM images were used separately, as well as together with the location variables for stratification of the first phase plots. There were, thus, a total of 16 combinations of auxiliary data to generate the stratifications. Correct percentages and Kappa values of the stratifications were used for comparing and assessing the accuracy of classifying peatland ecosystems.
   The results from the digital aerial photos showed that the combination of the window values in blue and red channels and six location variables led to the best classification. The total correct percentage and Kappa value were 90.9% and 0.416 for separating peatland and mineral soil, 92.9% and 0.849 for discriminating drained and undrained peatlands, 68.6% and 0.597 for classifying 7 biotope types, and 59.5% and 0.544 for classifying 16 biotope types. In addition, the optimal window size was different for each of the biotope types and digital channels. The classification was improved by location variables. TM images in addition to digital aerial photos did not improve the results.
