AB  - Lake Femund is a large (204 km(2)) oligotrophic Norwegian lake inhabited by eight fish species. European whitefish (Coregonus lavaretus) is the dominating fish species and can, for management purposes, be subdivided in three different morphs: Deep water spawning (D-) whitefish; River spawning (R-) whitefish; and Shallow water spawning (S-) whitefish. These morphs differ in habitat use, growth and life history characteristics and can be separated by differences in gill raker number. Traditionally, European whitefish was exploited with bottom gill nets and beach seine in subsistence fisheries. In 198 1, the start of a commercial fishery with pelagic gill nets increased the exploitation. The yield from this fishery has varied between 6 and 22 tone with declining yield in later years. This decline in yield was caused by a lower effort. CPUE of European whitefish decreased from 4.3 kg/netnight in 1982 to 1.2 kg/ netnight in 1987, but increased to a new peak in 1993, with 3.7 kg/netnight. The variation in overall CPUE closely followed the fluctuations in CPUE for D-whitefish, the most numerous morph in the lake. These fluctuations in CPUE were connected to variations in year class strength for D-whitefish, where recruitment appeared to alternate between stronger and weaker year classes over several years. Fewer variations were observed in the CPUE of R- and S-whitefish. Total annual mortality in adult fish was about 25-40% indicating that the catch mortality was not very high. Length-at-age of juvenile D-whitefish has decreased since the start of the commercial fishery, whereas that of adult fish has not changed much from 1983 to 1994. At the present level of exploitation, the fisheries in Lake Femund seems to be sustainable without strong effects on the density of adult European whitefish.
