AB  - The HERD Energy project QIMSEE (Quality Improvements of Master Programs in Sustainable Energy and Environment) is founded by the Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs. This project aims to contribute to educating a national work force at WB countries that has adequate innovative qualifications in the energy sector by building sustainable capacity of higher education institutions. The overall goal is to develop and establish new internationally recognized MSc study programs in accordance with Bologna Process for the field of "Sustainable Energy and Environment", at each of collaborating universities in the WB countries. More specific goals are amongst others to establish close cooperation between WB participants for mutual support in achieving better quality of master studies. Increase institutional quality and capacity of the WB Universities in the field of teaching staff improvement, laboratory organization and logistics, networking and supplementing expertise's to match closer to the Norwegian partners. Furthermore, to enhance connection and communication between the WB Universities and the industry/public sector in the WB region (Fig 1).
   In order to fulfill these tasks, and to conduct the activities specified in the project, it is crucial to design and implement a good physical/virtual learning environment. A technical backbone combined with new pedagogical methods, designed to incorporate a wide range of education technologies and to obtain enhanced collaboration and communication.
   The strategy is to divide the learning environment in modules or building block, which may be combined in different ways and adapted to the various activities/stages of the QIMSEE project. During the project period, a refinement process will extract the best ways of combining these building blocks, to create sustainable scenarios for learning and collaboration for the future.
   The challenge for many universities is to make a long term strategy regarding investment in education technology. There is a vast selection of equipment with different types of functionality. New solutions in educational technology are popping up every day, and it is hard to predict what will be the next established standard. In addition this technology should be implemented in cooperation with the IT-department, and the teachers need to get training and be inspired to adapt their content and pedagogical methods to the new educational technology. There is also a shift from the "one way communication" where the teacher talks and the students take notes, to a more varied learning environment. This environment might include interaction and collaboration, Student response systems, Peer instruction, MOOC, Flipped classroom, PBL and personalized learning techniques. In addition the students may use their own mobile devices in the learning process. (BOYD). All these factors have to be taken into consideration, when choosing the education technology for the future classroom.
