AB  - The EU and national policy goal to increase the share of renewable energy to 20 % of the total energy mix by 2020 is creating and will continue to create a growing demand for woody biomass. Woody biomass already provides 92 % of the renewable thermal energy in Germany. To secure the future sustainable supply of biomass, short rotation coppices (SRC) of fast-growing tree species such as willow and poplar are being established on arable land in Germany. This has led to a growing interest in finding out about the magnitude of the biomass potential using this form of cultivation. To evaluate amounts in Germany, GIS-based models were developed by MURACH et al. (2009) and AUST (2012) that calculate the biomass potential from water-management parameters, showing very different results. The approach chosen for the current study combines the methods of these studies and improves the calculation of evaporation, using the FAO-Penman-Monteith evapotranspiration and a crop coefficient of 1.2. Our modelling efforts suggest harvestable amounts of 117 million t/y of woody biomass from SRC on the maximum acreage of suitable sites all over Germany. However, the results of a more realistic (but still challenging) scenario of 300,000 ha of SRC, assuming an average biomass yield, project a capacity to supply 357,000 households with electricity and thermal energy or to provide 1.2 million households exclusively with electricity. Moreover, the findings also indicate that suitable sites are very heterogeneously distributed throughout Germany, which is largely related to groundwater availability. Therefore, the Northern German Plain is identified as a prime area for short rotation coppice systems. However, in regions with a negative climatic water balance, establishing SRC systems should be reconsidered or at least kept to a minimum due to the plants' high rate of water extraction, which could have negative effects on environmentally valuable wetlands and streams.
