AB  - In the article attention is focused on the following issues of forest sciences:
   1. Inference methods in forest sciences
   The empirical nature of forest research causes that inductionism has become the dominant method of building scientific theories in forestry. Its essence consists of making reference to reality, experience and experiment. The single observations obtained this way are generalized into hypotheses and laws explaining the functioning of the researched fragments of a forest and forest management. Even a large collection of observation data brings no certainty that all the forestry aspects interesting to us have been exhausted. Moreover, inductive inference means arriving at reason via consequence, i.e. the veracity of our reasoning depends on the authenticity of the consequence. Therefore, it is unreliable and, in general, limited to local Conditions. Because of the probabilistic nature of natural phenomena, the probabilistic Concept of inductive logic is becoming an important direction of reasoning development in empirical research.
   2. Interdisciplinary nature of forest research
   The development of forest knowledge entails growth in the number of branches of forest science. Their specialization, as well as atomization of research methods and tasks and practical activity are progressing. In this situation, the calls for inter- and trans-disciplinary forest research become particularly important; mainly to implement the concept of permanently sustainable and multifunctional forest management. It requires foresters' openness to innovative "external" disciplines, holistic approach to forest research and enhancement of the expert knowledge and role of foresters.
   3. Staff status in forest sciences
   The main forest research institutions in Poland are three forest departments of agricultural academies (in Cracow, Poznan and Warsaw), the IBL and the Institute of Dendrology of the Polish Academy of Sciences. These organizations have for many years been employing a total number of over 400 scientific staff. Also non-forest scientific institutions deal with forest research in addition to other disciplines The insufficient number of scientific staff is largely compensated by the development of forest doctoral studies. In 2005, over 200 candidates for a doctor's degree pursued their doctoral dissertations in forest scientific institutions.
   4. The organizational system and financing of forest studies
   Low spending on research in general is the main problem. In 2004, it amounted to only 0.58 of Gross Domestic Product of which 62% came from the State Budget, 23% from business entities and 5% from foreign sources. The expenses on research and development per capita in Poland amount to as little as 14% of the EU per capita average. This is why the proportion of scientific staff in the total population in Poland is 4: 1000, while in Finland the figure is over 16.
   5. Planning tasks for forest research
   Forest research results are important for many scientific disciplines and economy sectors. Therefore, their developmental needs are important in preparing the future programs, subjects and tasks of forest sciences. The Committee of Forest Sciences of the Polish Academy Of Sciences and the relevant bodies of the Ministry of Science and High Education, as well as the Ministry of the Environment are involved in the planning process. The last document specifying the future directions of science development in Poland is "The national framework program. The principles, procedure and subject range" developed in 2005. It is to be the basis for financing research, including forest research.
