AB  - During the first half of the 1980s, excavations were conducted in an area close to Skateholm, in the southernmost part of Sweden. The object of the project was to study the Mesolithic settlement around an ancient lagoon on the southern Scanian coast. The Late Atlantic oceanic transgressions had forced the society to seek shelter on ever-higher ground. At three sites, within the compass of an area no greater that 400 metres, graves dating to the period 6 300-5 700 BP were located to settlement areas. At two of these, almost ninety graves were excavated, showing a complicated mortuary practice with good evidence of the activities from the moment it was realized that the individual was clearly dying, up to the act of refilling the grave.
   Among the graves, 10 were dug for dogs. One grave contained a dog with an antler, a decorated antler artifact and three flint flakes as grave goods. Two categories of grave goods, antlers and blades are reminiscent of human graves. Among other factors which are similar to human graves is the strewing of red ochre over the corpse of the dog. The relation between dogs and humans can also be shown in a spatial perspective. Six of eight canine graves from the same cemetery lie within a delimited area.
   Two dogs appear to have been formally killed and placed in the human graves, and single skeletal parts occur in the filling in other human graves, which may mean that the animal was dismembered.
   The reason why dog graves have not been identified might be that they were not buried as deep as the humans as observed in Skateholm. However, dog interments have been found in other south Scandinavian sites form the Mesolithic, from both the late part as well as the old part of the period. Dogs have been found earlier in Mesolithic sites, but have been interpreted as discarded corpses.
   Buried dogs is a phenomenon which is known from the Late Palaeolithic. They were a part of the mortuary practice among hunter-gatherers in many parts of the world, such as Northern America and South-eastern Asia.
   During recent years archaeological research has been concentrated more than previously around the study of mortuary practices and what this can provide in terms of new information on the societies which the graves represent. Several researchers have tried to relate the graves to a hypothetical spiritual and social world with which the society surrounded itself. Others consider that the mortuary practices and cemeteries were used by certain members for the purpose of maintaining the existing social organization. Both points of view are equally valid in that the habitat of the dead provides an insight into the land of the living, and vice versa.
   Earlier theories which sought to show that interment during the Stone Age was a simple and uncomplicated affair have been confounded by recent discoveries of two, large-scale Mesolithic cemeteries in southernmost Sweden. These burials demonstrate, on the contrary, that burial customs during the period 6 300-5 700 BP were a complexity quite unknown during any other period of prehistory.
