T2  - HISTORISK TIDSSKRIFT
AB  - As far as I can determine, the concept "political culture" has not been much used in analyses of peasant resistance or in conflicts between the common people and the authorities in Norway in periods prior to 1800. In my study of the conflict between the circumference farmers and the ironworks owner, Bernt Anker, on the obligatory deliveries of charcoal, I have not limited my research to controversies, conflicts of interests and power structures. Through a close reading of the extremely rich source materials, I have tried to determine whether there is a pattern of underlying political culture. In defining "political culture" I have attached importance to several factors, most importantly the participants' political "range of action" in conflicts and decision-making. I have paid particular attention to the norms and rituals by means of which different groups or individuals exert influence in decision-making inside and outside bureaucratic channels. The range of action is not a constant factor, but instead is subject to pressures and change. As a result of skilful organization and effective measures the circumference farmers managed to shift the "political limits".
   The conflicts resulting from forcing these farmers to ensure the delivery of charcoal show that the common people had a relatively large political range of action. The farmers could deign to refuse or retard the production and delivery of charcoal without the authorities interpreting their acts as threats to social order or riot. The commission appointed by the Oberbergamt (chief mining office) in 1785 clearly expressed points of view indicating that refusals of delivery were not really considered punishable offences. The commission advised that the farmers should be persuaded rather than forced to make the deliveries, doubting that threats and sanctions would give the desired outcome.
   The central authorities tried, it is true, by legislation to prevent popular assemblies that could lead to riots. There has obviously been a great difference between law and reality. In the conflict between the Moss Ironworks and the circumference farmers, we can see that the authorities allowed the farmers extensive freedom of assembly, and complaints from the popular assemblies, letters of complaints from the local communities and the sending of peasant delegates to defend the farmers' interests, together with sabotage and delays, were not considered illegal actions. These types of action were at least to a certain extent accepted as part of the political culture, even though the owner of the Moss Iron Works considered them illegal.
