T2  - TUNA-AJALOOKULTUURI AJAKIRI
AB  - The most important factor in shaping borders in earlier times in Estonian territory has been nature, which has limited the area of human activity with deep forests, extensive swamps and bodies of water. The gradual replacement of the former zone or belt boundaries with linear boundaries began in association with the new power and ownership relationships that developed in the 13(th) century, and the growth in settlement density. As lands were enfeoffed, boundaries began to be determined ever more exactly and unambiguously. Thus, the former organic boundaries started being replaced by artificial boundaries that already had a clearly divisional and defensive function. This was accompanied by the adoption of artificial border markings as well. Rocks and trees marked with the sign of the cross were the two types of boundary markers that most easily enabled the marking of the kind of boundary that did not depend on natural conditions alone but rather on the will of people. Parts of civilised landscapes (roads, bridges, places of cult significance for pagans) were used to mark boundaries because they had an important part in local social-economic and cultural life and fostered the establishment of boundaries in the memory of local residents. Regardless of the growing importance of artificial boundary markers, the use of natural markers also continued alongside elements of the civilised landscape in marking boundaries due to the fact that linear parts of boundaries alternated with parts of boundaries that were not so exactly marked.
   A large number of dissimilar boundary markers were in use until the end of the 17(th) century from elements of the natural and civilised landscape to holes dug especially for marking boundaries, heaps of rocks, ditches, and marked rocks and trees. The use of trees as boundary markers was natural because they had already acquired landmark status in the landscape as well as in people's memories from time immemorial. Large trees have been important landmarks that made the work of land surveyors easier and made it possible to mark out boundary points without requiring any great effort. While the use of trees was common in the period when linear boundaries were evolving, the more exact and important linear boundaries of estates became, the less trees met the needs of marking this kind of boundary. Swedish authorities began bringing order to the marking of property boundaries at the end of the 17(th) century. Only boundary stones and posts planted upright in heaps of stones or soil were permitted for use as boundary markers and it was recommended to avoid using trees to mark boundaries because trees grow and their shape changes over time. There are few reports in folklore collections concerning trees as boundary markers because the use of trees as boundary markers began dying out in the 17(th) century already.
   The replacement of the former belt or zone boundaries with linear boundaries took centuries in Estonian territory. Exact linear boundaries did not become predominant until the end of the 17(th) century and not properly until the 18(th) and 19(th) centuries in swamp and forest areas. Boundary space became the boundary line, for which reason the formerly common natural boundary markers were abandoned and only boundary posts planted upright in heaps of stones or soil and boundary stones marked with crosses were used to mark boundaries. The evolution of boundaries and boundary markers is associated with more general demographic, economic and social evolution, whereas the standardisation of the marking of boundaries also demonstrates the regulation of ownership relationships and the consolidation of power.
